{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632276"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:38:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:38:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17429"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17429"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0,0.1,0.1,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70772"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5341"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23798"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70772"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe term \u0027obesogenic environment\u0027 describes characteristics of modern communities that contribute to increasing rates of obesity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary characteristic of an obesogenic environment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Promotes sedentary behaviour through urban design","Increases exposure to endocrine-disrupting chemicals","Reduces access to affordable fresh produce","Creates social norms favouring high-calorie foods","Promotes unhealthy behaviours while limiting healthy choices"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eobesogenic environment promotes unhealthy behaviours while limiting healthy choices\u003C/strong\u003E through various physical and social factors. These include poor access to healthy food options, high density of fast food outlets, limited green spaces, car-dependent infrastructure, and barriers to physical activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes sedentary behaviour through urban design\u003C/strong\u003E is one component but not the complete picture of obesogenic environments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases exposure to endocrine-disrupting chemicals\u003C/strong\u003E: while environmental chemicals may affect metabolism, this is not a defining characteristic of obesogenic environments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces access to affordable fresh produce\u003C/strong\u003E: this is one aspect but does not capture the full scope of environmental influences on obesity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreates social norms favouring high-calorie foods\u003C/strong\u003E: social influences are important but represent only one facet of obesogenic environments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding obesogenic environments is crucial for developing effective public health interventions that target both individual behaviour and environmental factors contributing to obesity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Obesogenic environments are physical and social settings that promote weight gain by encouraging excess caloric intake and discouraging physical activity.","Key features of obesogenic environments include high density of fast food outlets, limited access to healthy foods, and poor infrastructure for physical activity.","Urban planning and policy interventions can help reduce the impact of obesogenic environments on population health."],"references":["Mackenbach JD, Rutter H, Compernolle S, et al. Obesogenic environments: a systematic review of the association between the physical environment and adult weight status, the SPOTLIGHT project. BMC Public Health. 2014;14:233. Published 2014 Mar 6. doi:10.1186/1471-2458-14-233","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17429"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:55:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:57:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70772"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.e